## Level 13 → Level 14
**Objective:** No password this time — log into bandit14 using an RSA
private key stored in a file on the bandit13 server.

**Commands Used:**
```bash
# On bandit13 server:
ls                              # found sshkey.private file
cat ~/sshkey.private            # revealed the RSA private key contents

# On local Kali machine:
nano ~/bandit14.private         # created a new file and pasted the key
                                # Ctrl+X → Y → Enter to save and exit
chmod 600 ~/bandit14.private    # set correct permissions on key file
ssh -i ~/bandit14.private bandit14@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220
                                # logged into bandit14 using the key
```

**What is an RSA Private Key?**
- A private key is an alternative to passwords for SSH authentication
- Much more secure than passwords — nearly impossible to brute force
- Stored as a text file with a specific format:
```
-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
[many lines of random looking characters]
-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----
```
- The header and footer lines are NOT decorative — they are part of
  the key format. SSH will reject the key without them

**How `-i` Flag Works in SSH:**
```bash
# Normal SSH with password:
ssh bandit14@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220

# SSH with private key file:
ssh -i ~/bandit14.private bandit14@bandit.labs.overthewire.org -p 2220
# -i = identity file — tells SSH to use a key file instead of password
```

**Why `chmod 600` is Required:**
- SSH refuses to use a private key if its permissions are too open
- If other users can read your key it is considered compromised
- `chmod 600` = owner can read and write, everyone else has no access
- Without this step SSH throws a permission error and won't connect

**Permission Numbers Explained:**
| chmod | Owner | Group | Others |
|---|---|---|---|
| `600` | read+write | none | none |
| `644` | read+write | read | read |
| `700` | all | none | none |
| `777` | all | all | all |

**Two Terminal Window Workflow:**
- Terminal 1 — connected to bandit13, used to cat the key
- Terminal 2 — local Kali machine, used to create key file and connect
- Never disconnect bandit13 until bandit14 connection is confirmed

**Mistakes Made and Fixed:**
- Initially copied key without the header and footer lines →
  SSH threw "error in libcrypto" error
- Fix: always copy the entire key including
  `-----BEGIN RSA PRIVATE KEY-----` and `-----END RSA PRIVATE KEY-----`

**What I Learned:**
- Private keys are more secure than passwords for SSH authentication
- The `-i` flag in SSH specifies a key file to use for login
- Private key files must have `chmod 600` permissions or SSH rejects them
- The header and footer lines of a key file are essential — never skip them
- `nano` is used to create and edit files directly in the terminal

**Key Takeaway:**
In real pentesting, finding a private key file on a system is a
huge win — it can give you direct SSH access to other servers
without needing any password. Always look for `.private`, `.pem`,
or `id_rsa` files when exploring a compromised system.
